content.description: Start at the base of a 7-8" wide dirty flare and climb the face up the right side.
content.location: Second route from the right. Route crosses a wide crack.

content.description: Start straight in the crack and move right to the high first bolt. Trend up and right.
content.location: Third route from the left. Just right of a dirty crack.

content.description: A dirty adventure up loose blocks on the far right of the cliff. There is a 4th class scramble/solo to the right of this route that you can access TR on other routes if so desired.
A few good edges lead to a finger crack that protects with stoppers. The slightly dirty middle section will clean up with time. There are two bolts that protect the upper headwall with good holds.
content.protection: Stoppers and small cams lead to two bolts up high. Two bolt anchor. (Hangers only)
content.location: Thin crack right of Sand Wedge.

content.description: Start at an old downed tree stump. Pull a contrived mantle to a low angle slab. Traverse right to the crack. Grab large holds to an alcove with a distinct crux. Keep an eye out for the fearless lizard the route is named after on the belay ledge. He will try to tell you what's up.
content.protection: 4 bolts to a two bolt anchor with one quicklink and a bail biner.
content.location: Furthest route right. By a tree bench.

content.description: Contrived start to avoid the block. Climb a dirty corner to the first bolt. Traverse right on thin crimps to large holds. Crux between 1st and 3rd clip. Large block(s) that looks like it will topple if you touch it located to the right is off (obviously).
content.location: Belay on the conveniently located square patch of grass left of Bogey. Furthest route to the left.

content.description: Climb the face and the right side of the crack. For a more challenging (.10+) variation try to stay out of the crack to the right.
content.location: Second bolt line from the left. Just left of a dirty crack.

content.description: Start straight in the crack and climb it for about 35' take care moving past a small tree when the crack peters out break right and go directly through the steepest part of the roof on cool holds.
content.protection: 2-bolt anchor. Gear to 2-3" mostly hand size and a few stoppers. A cool trad headpoint. The upper half is good just unprotected.
content.location: Hand crack right of Mothballs with some blocks at the start.
